\cf0 \'95	Tapping on the paintbrush icon brings up the formatting palette, which should be familiar to anyone who has used Pages. (On the iPhone, this icon is only available from the extended keyboard row\'97see below.) Note that although Scrivener allows you a great deal of control over the formatting, it is not intended as a replacement for a word processor\'97Scrivener is about hammering out your words. (It is not meant for advanced layout tasks such as wrapping text around images, for example.)\
\'95	The magnifying glass brings up Find and Replace.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\sl336\slmult1\sb260\partightenfactor0
\cf0 While you type, a live word count appears in the nav bar at the top of the screen. (You can change this to a character count\'97or have both\'97via the options in Settings app.) When you end editing, the word count appears in the toolbar at the bottom of the screen (iPad only).\
Note that, by default, Scrivener uses smart typography\'97so quotation marks, double- and triple-hyphens, and ellipses all get converted to their smart equivalents as you type. You can turn this off via Settings app if you prefer, and you can also change the type of quotes used for different languages.\
